<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://trashotron.com/agony/columns/05-24-02.htm">trashotron.com/agony/colu...-24-02.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://home.earthlink.net/~markreiff/projects/guest/mook.html">home.earthlink.net/~markr.../mook.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.serve.com/guilds/astro/rtsccnbw_unssp.txt">www.serve.com/guilds/astr..._unssp.txt</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.serve.com/guilds/astro/racsarc_unssp.txt">www.serve.com/guilds/astr..._unssp.txt</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.serve.com/guilds/astro/rposei2050_unssp.txt">www.serve.com/guilds/astr..._unssp.txt</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.serve.com/guilds/astro/rlacsd_unssp.txt">www.serve.com/guilds/astr..._unssp.txt</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
&gt; I know<br>
&gt; that the shape of the nuclear bombs would minimized EMP,<br>
<br>
Yes.<br>
<br>
&gt; but not being a<br>
&gt; nuclear physist, I had no way to calculate these changes, so my simple<br>
computer<br>
&gt; program was the best I could do.<br>
<br>
Well, nuclear physics is part of physics. If you're calculating Compton<br>
Scattering, the mathematics and physical process is pretty straightforward.<br>
To get really really big EMP effects requires a special set of conditions.<br>
If those conditions don't occur, then EMP effects will be limited. Its not<br>
trivial, but still easy engineering-wise, to build your thrust system so<br>
that EMP effects are minimized. That's my only point.<br>
<br>
&gt;Also, most specifics in nuclear bomb technology<br>
&gt; are still classified,<br>
<br>
That's true. But, this goes to making and detonating a weapon. Nature, and<br>
science are not classified. The basic processes are well understood and<br>
amenable to calculation by any knowledgeable scientist. Which is the<br>
problem those who wish to halt proliferation face.<br>
<br>
&gt; really causing problems finding that information.<br>
<br>
Again, the basic physical processes are well understood, and the science and<br>
engineering for purposes of estimating Nuclear Pulse performance rather<br>
straightforward. While the details for efficient construction and compact<br>
deployment and so forth are classified, the basic processes are not.<br>
<br>
For fission bombs you start with a sub-critical mass of fissile material,<br>
generally in spherical form, and compress it to criticality. The figure of<br>
merit is the mean free path of neutrons versus density and neutron flux.<br>
Mean free path is a function of nuclear cross-sections, which is easily<br>
looked up. All you need to know is spherical integration procedures to<br>
figure out critical mass versus density. The compressibility of<br>
highly-compressed metals is pretty well available in any reference book.<br>
This along with some basic physics gives you the work function needed to<br>
attain that compresssion. From this you calculate the enthalpy needed to<br>
attain various levels of compression. You can then compare these results<br>
with levels of compression achievable with chemical explosives, and levels<br>
of compression achieved with a variety of inertical confinement fusion<br>
techniques (z-pinch, theta-pinch, electron beam, laser, etc.) to figure out<br>
the minimal critical masses possible with these. All the while<br>
understanding that detailed designs that actually work will require many<br>
many fine nuances not discussed in this broad stroke approach taken here.<br>
To get to anti-proton enhanced microfission, you need to read the papers<br>
published on that. In publications like FUSION. The critical piece of data<br>
is that an antiproton mixed in with a Pu-240 nucleus at the right time leads<br>
to a fission process that releases 9 neutrons (not 2) and a fair chance of<br>
generating the antiproton again. Thus, the antiprotons are truely<br>
catalysts. With this production rate you go back to your mean free path<br>
calculations with a much larger neutron flux growth and repeat the process,<br>
to end up with a much smaller critical mass throughout.<br>
<br>
For fusion bombs all you need to know is Lawson Criterion, the thermal<br>
density required in a plasma to create a self-sustaining nuclear reacition.<br>
If you don't achieve this energy density, the fusion process won't self<br>
propagate. If you do achieve this energy density, the fusion process will<br>
grow.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.rzg.mpg.de/~bds/phys/lawson-criterion.html">www.rzg.mpg.de/~bds/phys/...erion.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
The URL above has more info on this.<br>
<br>
None of this is classified. Once you figure out the Lawson Criterion for<br>
whatever plasma you're working with, you can use your fission explosion to<br>
provide the needed thermal flux. Here, the trick is depositing the energy<br>
into the plasma before it boils away. So, your explosion has to be quick.<br>
This is what Inertial Confinement means!<br>
<br>
Its also no secret that the best way to do this is with intense gamma rays<br>
from an atom blast.<br>
<br>
Heck, Encyclopedia Britannica used to have a picture of a 'triple-decker'<br>
fusion bomb with a cutaway!<br>
<br>
The whole thing was the size of a big football. An ellipsoid of revolution<br>
made out of a variety of materials designed to reflect gamma rays within a<br>
specific range of energies. At one focus of the ellipsoid was a fission<br>
bomb. A tiny pea sized piece of Polonium, a neutron source. Surrounding<br>
that was a larger, baseball sized piece of Plutonium. Around that was a<br>
grapefruit sized piece of plastic explosive. Not shown were the details<br>
between the Plutonium and C4 interface, that focused the energy of the C4<br>
explosive, and the case surrounding the C4. At the other focus was a<br>
grapefruit sized piece of Lithium Deuteride, surrounded by a thin sheet of<br>
styrofoam like material, that boiled away when illuminated with intense<br>
gamma rays. Surrounding the whole device on the outside of the football was<br>
a layer of depleted Uranium, about an inch thick.<br>
<br>
 In operation, the bomb operated like clock work.<br>
<br>
(1) The C4 went off, and<br>
(2) the shock wave compressed the Plutonium, while<br>
(3) the case (not shown) contained the C4 explosion.<br>
(4) The Plutonium went off when it achieved criticality,<br>
(5) Which produced intense gamma rays,<br>
(6) The gamma rays were refocused onto the second foci,<br>
(7) Which boiled off the styrofoam,<br>
(<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Which compressed the Lithium Deuteride<br>
(9) Increasing gamma radiation heated the increasingly dense plasma until<br>
(10) It fused to form Helium<br>
(11) Releasing lots of neutrons<br>
(12) Which were absorbed by the depleted Uranium<br>
(13) Which caused it to convert to Pu-239, Pu-240,<br>
(14) Which under these conditions fissioned<br>
<br>
This triple decker design could release between 10 Megatons and 50 Megatons<br>
and be carried in a steamer trunk.<br>
<br>
Again, the details of getting a working bomb that actually did what you<br>
wanted it to, rather than make a big messy heap of molten Plutonium, were<br>
classified. But, the basic physics, and engineering is plain to see.<br>
<br>
Its clear that this design could be reduced in size with the introduction of<br>
a microfission device, since the size of the fissile trigger here is<br>
determined by minimum critical mass. Also, since we don't want to release a<br>
lot of fissile material into the environment, we dispense with depleted<br>
uranium 'booster'.<br>
<br>
Early designs for magentically propelled ICFusion pellets give us an idea of<br>
what a microfission device might look like. Basically, a bit of enriched<br>
Plutonium wire, bent into a specific shape. Looking a lot like a bent<br>
paperclip. This is at one focus of a bomblet, far smaller in size than the<br>
bomb just described. An ellipsoid of revolution about the size of a large<br>
egg has a small bent paperclip at one focus and a marble sized bit of Li-D<br>
at the other focus, encased in a small shell of styrene. Surrounding the<br>
egg or off to one side, is a big super-capacitor a little larger than the<br>
egg itself. In operation the egg is fired into position by a guided round<br>
and when the electronics aboard determine its at the right spot, the<br>
capacitor shorts out through the Plutonium paperclip. The plutonium clip,<br>
through the action of self induced magnetic fields, collapses on itself<br>
achieving very symmetrical, and very intense pressures. The Plutonium<br>
detonates when it achieves criticality, releasing a burst of gamma rays,<br>
among other things. The gamma rays set boil off the styrene, which<br>
compressed the fusion fuel. Increasingly intense gamma rays heat the<br>
compressing fuel until fusion takes place. In the end, you have a 20 ton<br>
TNT equivalent fission yeild producing a 20,000 to 40,000 ton TNT equivalent<br>
fusion yeild - with very little radiological release.<br>
<br>
All this is pretty straightforward engineering and physics, requiring no<br>
access to classified literatureor processes.<br>
<br>
&gt; I am somewhat farmiliar in the fact that ISP matching the mission would<br>
help<br>
&gt; signifigantly.<br>
<br>
Yes. That's why low ISP may be interesting for Earth escape, and then<br>
switch to high ISP when free of Earth's biosphere. Sort of like switching<br>
gears.<br>
<br>
&gt; It is also likely true that it could save lives by providing<br>
&gt; larger sources of raw materials,<br>
<br>
Yes.<br>
<br>
&gt; on the same token, it could also cause hyper-inflation<br>
&gt; and cause those who are poor to starve to death.<br>
<br>
That's not true. Hyper-inflation, or inflation (otherwise known as a<br>
general rise in all prices) of any sort, is caused by too many dollars<br>
chasing too few goods. This usually comes about because governments need to<br>
finance operations - such as war, or recovery from recession, or excessive<br>
government operations - by printing money. This can happen even if the<br>
government decides to print just a little more money than it collects.<br>
Deflation, (or a general fall in all prices), is the opposite. This is<br>
generally caused by a reduction in demand for products. This can be caused<br>
by a large number of processes, but most significantly, by a lack of<br>
credit - such as that which caused the Great Depression of 1929. (Read<br>
Milton Friedman, FREE TO CHOOSE for more information on this).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0156334607/inktomi-bkasin-20/103-6443">www.amazon.com/exec/obido...0/103-6443</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
874-0041416<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.freetochoose.com/">www.freetochoose.com/</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Milton is a Nobel Prize winning economist who was active during the<br>
Roosevelt Administration as well as the Reagan Administration.<br>
<br>
In more recent times (as in the Nixon and Ford and Carter Administrations)<br>
STAGFLATION was a problem. This was increasing prices with decreasing<br>
demand. Sort of a mix of the worst of deflation and inflation. This is<br>
caused by excessive taxation. What's excessive? Taxation beyond the<br>
SCHUMPETER LIMIT.<br>
<br>
Generally speaking, free economies operate as follows. Entrepreneurs invest<br>
in new business activity to meet unmet demands, in the process they hire<br>
managers and workers. The managers and workers make stuff or provide<br>
services for which they are paid. With their money they buy stuff. The new<br>
business also buys stuff raw materials, advertising and so forth. The rest<br>
is profit for the creator of the business. They buy stuff too, but they<br>
also invest to grow their business wherever possible. In this way the<br>
economy grows meeting more and more needs of more and more people.<br>
<br>
Now, please note, I am not using terms like entrepreneurs, managers,<br>
workers, and so forth to indicate 'classes' of people (as a socialist or<br>
communist might). I refer only to these as functions people perform. In a<br>
free and open society such classes don't really exist. People can and do<br>
engage in all these activities. For example, a next door neighbor of mine<br>
worked at a retail store for a number of years, started a restaurant, built<br>
it up, sold it, invested in the market, went back to work for another<br>
retailer as a store manager. This person doesn't fall into any class, but<br>
fulfills all the functions described above at different times of their<br>
lives.<br>
<br>
Governments do things that people need or want, but for which they are<br>
unwilling to pay for in the market. People want fire protection, police,<br>
armies, street lights, water service, for example, but don't want to buy it<br>
the way they buy tickets to a fight, or batteries, or bottled water. So,<br>
they agree to pay taxes to fund development of government operations and<br>
sometimes to even pay service fees to buy services from the new government<br>
operation.<br>
<br>
Governments do not make profits and do not sell things in competition with<br>
others who challenge them to be more efficient. Governments also do not<br>
sell things that people are willing to pay for in a market, because if there<br>
was a market for the things government did, there'd be no need for<br>
government programs or operatoins to provide those things.<br>
<br>
As far as the productive entrepreneurial side of the economy goes,<br>
government is a black hole that sucks up money and provide less return than<br>
it costs in an economic sense - even though what governments produce might<br>
be popular. So, government grows at the expense of the productivity of the<br>
free-economy.<br>
<br>
When taxes are so high that entrepreneurs must shut down their businesses<br>
and sell off the assets to pay their taxes, that's when stagflation occurs.<br>
Also, when governments interfere with the operation of business, either<br>
through legitimate concerns such as pollution, or public concerns such as<br>
safety, as in the case of licensing restaurant operators, or wages, as in<br>
minimum wages, they increase the cost of doing business, without providing a<br>
compensating return to the people who must pay for these things. This also<br>
creates stagflation.<br>
<br>
Actually, a careful analysis shows that inflation, especially<br>
hyperinflation, is caused by a government that prints money to pay for its<br>
programs because its people cannot or will not pay taxes to support those<br>
programs. Deflation can be caused by a variety of factors, but the most<br>
important is a reduction in the available money supply. This most typically<br>
is caused by government failure to properly manage the money supply, or<br>
caused by excessive taxation, or caused by excessive regulation or all<br>
three. Stagflation is caused by a combination of excessive<br>
taxation/regulation and government spending beyond their receipts.<br>
<br>
Please note, I'm not using the word 'excessive' in any pejorative sense.<br>
What is excessive in one economic melieu may be easily sustainable in<br>
another. It depends totally on the profitability enjoyed by businesses.<br>
I'm also not anti-government. Governments are very important to a society.<br>
Its just that they have fewer ways to guarantee their activities won't wreck<br>
an economy. In fact, there's another Nobel prize winning economist, Ken<br>
Arrow, who proved that governments are incapable of such regulation (read<br>
Arrow's, SOCIAL CHOICE AND HUMAN VALUES).<br>
<br>
Bottom line, for our discussion though, is in none of these cases is the<br>
availability of low-cost energy and low-cost raw materials the source of<br>
economic difficulty.<br>
<br>
If my proposal was a $1.2 trillion government program, that produced ships<br>
of little or no economic utility, or didn't produce or operate ships at all,<br>
then it would cause problems. But, the world has spent $5 trillion arming<br>
itself with nuclear weapons and we're still accumulating capital - with only<br>
a few reversals. So, I don't think it would cause inflation or<br>
hyperinflation as you think.<br>
<br>
If my proposal caused private sector entrepreneurs to risk $1.2 trillion and<br>
it didn't work, it would cause some economic difficulty. But, the world has<br>
spent $6 trillion over the last ten years burying optical fiber - for which<br>
the world needed only $1 trillion worth of fiber. This has caused a lot of<br>
losses, and some economic difficulty, but not a great depression. So, the<br>
total failure of a private effort to build nuclear pulse is unlikely to<br>
cause major problems.<br>
<br>
If my proposal caused private sector entrepreneurs to capture a $3.0<br>
trillion per year raw materials, energy, and communications markets, it<br>
would spell the end of traditional businesses in these areas. But, that is<br>
an adjustment that is easy for the market to account for. This happened in<br>
the telecom and computer business with massive changes in the way these<br>
products were made and these services rendered. It will happen here. A<br>
coal company may become an operator of solar recievers for example, a<br>
bauxite mining operation may become a distributor for aluminum powder from<br>
space. While these dislocations will cause massive turnover in affected<br>
businesses, more efficient production of these materials and energy and<br>
services, using space based assets and resources, will provide the basis for<br>
greater profits worldwide, and fuel an expansion of business.<br>
<br>
Deflation could happen if<br>
<br>
(1) A single business captured control of the major material, energy and<br>
communications markets,<br>
(2) This business used its monopoly position to raise prices,<br>
<br>
(NOTE: prices must be raised, since market penetration couldn't occur<br>
without competitive prices at first)<br>
<br>
But this could not be sustainable unless the business monopoly got the<br>
government to outlaw competition (which could happen if laws were passed to<br>
limit pollution on Earth frex). Without such regulatory restriction, any<br>
monopoly would be broken. Actually, proper regulation of competition of the<br>
early development of space resources would guarantee this would never<br>
happen. So, this sort of deflation is unlikely because its so easily<br>
predictable and avoided.<br>
<br>
In short, there is no way lower cost materials, energy, communications<br>
services, delivered from space, could cause a deflation, inflation,<br>
hyperinflation, or stagflation. Vast quantities of materials and energy and<br>
information from space would dislocate many many businesses on Earth today,<br>
but they would do so by creating far more value than is lost by those<br>
businesses. So, those businesses will either adapt to the new conditions,<br>
to make more money, or the old businesses will go belly up, and the<br>
resources made available at auction, will be used by newer businesses to<br>
make more money.<br>
<br>
&gt; It would also put large<br>
&gt; numbers of people out of work who work in the mining industry,<br>
<br>
Yep. But, if the total cost of raw materials and energy declines, the usage<br>
of raw materials and energy goes up (supply and demand) and living standard<br>
overall rises. In short, some businesses will fail, but others will be<br>
created, and society in general will be ahead. For example, the<br>
introduction of the automobile caused buggy whip manufacturers to go out of<br>
business. But, the cost of transporting goods and people dropped<br>
dramatically with autos. Horses were costly, capricious, dangerous, dirty,<br>
and of limited range. Horses and trains together were logistical nighmares.<br>
Autos replaced all this with a cost effective alternative. As a result, the<br>
entire society was wealthier - despite the obsolescence of whole hosts of<br>
industry. Those obsolete businesses didn't stand in line for a hand out.<br>
They reinvented themselves, or the entrepreneurs started new businesses.<br>
All the horse outfitters in every town became full service gas stations.<br>
Buggy upolsterers became battery repair and replacement centers. At the end<br>
of the day, some people went out of business, most people changed the focus<br>
of existing businesses to take advantage of the changes, and some people<br>
went into new businesses that weren't possible before autos (like Ray Kroc<br>
who invented the first national drive-thru chain, McDonalds).<br>
<br>
&gt; and while<br>
&gt; it would create jobs, it would take some serious research to determine if<br>
&gt; there would be a net creation of jobs.<br>
<br>
The research has already been done and is known by economists. Not for this<br>
specific project, but in general, we already know that if the cost of doing<br>
something is less with new technology, then the introduction of that<br>
technology (all things being equal) will result in a net creation of jobs.<br>
So, all we must do as morally responsible citizens is guarantee that the new<br>
system we create will produce energy at less $/joule and less $/watt than<br>
existing systems. That thenew system of mining and manufacturing will<br>
produce materials and deliver them to customers at less $/kg of material.<br>
But, this is the same thing any business seeks. We must deliver things at<br>
lower cost to be competitive. When we are successful in doing so, then we<br>
automatically guarantee those savings spread to everyone in society through<br>
operation of a free market.<br>
<br>
Now, as moral citizens we also must concern ourselves with third party<br>
effects. These relate to safety, environmental quality, social impact. If<br>
products we make are unsafe, if they pollute, or if they cause social<br>
problems - it doesn't matter how economically beneficial they are, they<br>
cannot do these things. But, gathering materials and energy from space, and<br>
using space as a platform to broadcast broadband internet services to<br>
Earth - has none of these.<br>
<br>
The only issues in this vein are the radiological release of the nuclear<br>
pulse rocket, and the disposal of wastes from a world with 7 to 8 billion<br>
citizens consuming materials at current US per capita rates. The first I've<br>
already addressed by showing that radiation is actually reduced. The<br>
second, I've yet to address with you, but have given some thought to. I<br>
won't bore you with details now, since I've already typed loads! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
&gt; It's all relative, and the only real<br>
&gt; way to test the theory is to actually build one and launch it.<br>
<br>
I agree. But, much can be done. And, as a business person who's started<br>
some successful businesses, there are a few practical matters. I favor a 3<br>
stage development program;<br>
<br>
(1) $10 million - early research and promotion - This basically uses<br>
lobbyists in DC to gain special privileges to early researchers so they may<br>
use national assets for development and test, and retain the exclusive<br>
rights to mine asteroids, and also have the right to operate nuclear pulse<br>
vehicles if guidelines are met;<br>
<br>
(2) $10 billion - intermediate R&amp;D - This basically uses existing nuclear<br>
weapons research centers in the US, along with existing national space<br>
assets, to model mathematically, build test fixtures, operate test<br>
equipment, leading to a proof of concept vehicle, resulting in a<br>
demonstration fleet capable of solar system wide operation;<br>
<br>
(3) $1,400 billion - final fleet build out - Based on R&amp;D results, a nuclear<br>
pulse fleet is built capable of harvesting large amounts of asteroidal<br>
material, and also placing large networks of factorysats, powersats, and<br>
infosats into LEO, to sustain a large and growing market on Earth;<br>
<br>
